title: Migrated DS
reason: This research is under the DHS DDoSD project (TTA 2: DDoS Defense for a Community of Peers), 3DCoP. Resulting software will be released as open-source.We are developing a collaborative model in which organizations detect and mitigate attacks together by sharing anonymized traffic metrics through a Peer-to-Peer network. Our model allows an organization under attack to automatically coordinate with its service provider(s) to drop the right packets and remain on-line. Other networks, such as unwitting contributors to the attack, can also respond to the attack by dropping malicious packets.3DCoP allows participating organizations to mutually benefit from collaborative defense. The result is faster mitigation, at more points of the Internet, and less down time for everyone.Data from past DDoS attacks will be used to help develop anomaly detection, and also to help develop our system architecture. We will manually inspect the data to better understand packet characteristics of attacks.

reason: We are a contractor with DHS S&T CSD tasked with testing and evaluation of DHS funded technologies. The goal of the testing is to evaluate how the application represents known data and anomalous network activity. title: Migrated DS
researchLocations: 5042 Technology Parkway Suite 100, Fort Collins, Colorado 80528
reason: Numerica Corp. is requesting this dataset (titled 'SKAION 2006 IARPA Dataset' ) to support the technical objectives of a small business innovation research (SBIR) contract, titled "Novel Detection Mechanisms for Advanced Persistent Threats." The project is funded by the Navy, specifically the Naval Warfare Systems Command. The main objective of the project that relates to the requested datasets is to assess the performance of Numerica's advanced persistent threat (APT) detection algorithms on realistic network intrusion scenarios. Using the requested datasets, analysis of both the algorithmic performance and the software implementation of Numerica's approach would be performed. Of particular importance to our objectives are realistic computer network datasets  that capture both  'normal' and 'malicious' user activity. The SKAION dataset being requested would be ideal for our research purposes, since it provides such network data without compromising the privacy of users, in formats that Numerica's algorithms are already being designed to interface with. In addition, the dataset documents the complete known "ground truth" - that is, which network traffic is benign and which traffic is malicious. Thus, the dataset will help to identify strengths of Numerica's approach to APT detection, areas where improvement is necessary and/or possible, and any computational performance limitations.

title: Migrated DS
reason: Accelogic, LLC has recently been awarded SBIR (Small Business Innovation Research) contract number W911NF-16-C-0019 by DARPA. I am the Principal Investigator for this project. The main purpose of this contract is to design and implement the fundamental theory and methods of a groundbreaking technology for injecting extreme-speed acceleration into graph analytics software. This technology will support seamless acceleration of virtually any graph API (e.g., STINGER, Neo4j, GraphLab, Spark, OrientDB), and will take advantage of a variety of underlying hardware systems, including multi-core CPUs, GPUs, MICs, FPGA systems, or any combination of these. During the initial phase of the project we will develop a proof-of-concept prototype that will demonstrate the technologyÃ¢Â€Â™s ability to provide orders-of-magnitude acceleration for graph analytics. We are currently developing said prototype and plan to validate it with both real-life and synthetically generated data that gets analyzed for anomaly detection in a cybersecurity context. In this regard, we have chosen the following datasets from the DARPA SNM Program Traffic as valuable to our project:DARPA_2009_malware-DDoS_attack-20091104346.5MBPCAPand DARPA_2009_DDoS_attack-200911051.01GBPCAPPlease do not hesitate to contact me if there is any other information you require.Juan Gonzalez, Ph.D.PresidentAccelogic, LLC

title: Migrated DS
reason: This research is under the DHS DDoSD project (TTA 2: DDoS Defense for a Community of Peers), 3DCoP. Resulting software will be released as open-source.We are developing a collaborative model in which organizations detect and mitigate attacks together by sharing anonymized traffic metrics through a Peer-to-Peer network. Our model allows an organization under attack to automatically coordinate with its service provider(s) to drop the right packets and remain on-line. Other networks, such as unwitting contributors to the attack, can also respond to the attack by dropping malicious packets.3DCoP allows participating organizations to mutually benefit from collaborative defense. The result is faster mitigation, at more points of the Internet, and less down time for everyone.Data from past DDoS attacks will be used to help develop anomaly detection, and also to help develop our system architecture. We will manually inspect the data to better understand packet characteristics of attacks. We also may generate netflow/ipfix flows from the data to test out our software's response (internal testing only).
datasetOrg: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

Other networks, such as unwitting contributors to the attack, can also respond to the attack by dropping malicious packets.3DCoP allows participating organizations to mutually benefit from collaborative defense. The result is faster mitigation, at more points of the Internet, and less down time for everyone.Data from past DDoS attacks will be used to help develop anomaly detection, and also to help develop our system architecture. We will manually inspect the data to better understand packet characteristics of attacks. We also may generate netflow/ipfix flows from the data to test out our software's response (internal testing only).

reason: RedJack, working with Noblis, is developing and evaluating analysis algorithms and tools to provide rapid analysis of large scale data. Among the techniques are graph based approaches to identifying communities of interest, similarity analyses to identify related connection traces, etc.  The data will be used to test a variety of tools and implementations, including those developed in house as well as others.  The requested dataset is particularly useful for these purposes since it contains some TB of packet data and will easily demonstrate the scalability of the proposed approaches. In addition, its provenance as artificial data avoids sensitivity issues associated with live captures.

reason: GUARDIAN is a 24-month development effort funded by USTRANSCOM. The approach is to use a combination of fast single-signal statistical anomaly detection and deep multi-dimensional Pattern Classification and Machine Learning algorithms to detect multi-stage "slow and low" network attacks. The data will be used as input to both the fast single-signal algorithms and the deep "big data" components. We want to use this data set because it contains a variety of different information formats. Feature Set Reduction using Principal Component Analysis is an important topic for investigation.

reason: BAA Number: IMC-13Name of Offeror: Glimmerglass Optical Cyber SolutionsTrack Number: TRACK 1: DATA DISCOVERY, ANALYSIS, EXPLOITATION, AND MANAGEMENTTopic Number(s): TOPIC 7. Data Discovery CapabilitiesProposal Title: Proposal to Integrate Fiber Optic Link Hierarchical Stream Metadata with Internet Protocol Metadata Ã¢Â€Â“ A Standard Model for Integrating OSI Layer 1 and 2 Path Name Value Pairs (Tuples) with Layer 3 through 7 Protocol and Application TuplesContract Award: H98230-13-C-1420My company is working on an NSA BAA (Broad Agency Announcement) award to investigate the ability to connect Layer 3 through 7 network data streams with Layer 1 and 2 Optical fiber link and synchronous data hierarchy.  We are creating a test bench to inject real network traffic, from PCAPs, into TDM (PDH/SDH) structures, decoding and extracting these TDM structures, and then passing this data on to networking probes where we extract the Networking through Application information.  We join the layers L1&2 to L3-7 in order to show how we may be able to detect native circuits and use all of the layers of information to learn of the source of the original signal.Since we are not a telco or have access to large layer 3-7 data sources, PCAPs, we have been using NSA BAA recommended sources for real traffic.Our demonstration expires October 17, 2013 and we will dispose of any trace files from PREDICT that have been used in conjunction with this project.

reason: CCRi proposes to develop a prototype online network traffic anomaly detection system (Aspen) that adaptively learns and updates a dynamic model for normal network traffic flow from a multivariate vector of network flow attributes. The Aspen prototype will be designed to be connected to an external source of periodically-updated NetFlow datagrams. For development and demonstration purposes, archival NetFlow datasets obtained from PREDICT (www.predict.org) will be used. Aspen will identify network traffic flow that does not conform to the current model expectation. Recent network traffic data and anomaly results will be stored in an Accumulo database. The system will provide a periodically-updated visual display to inform and alert users.

reason: Department of Defense (DoD) operations are supported by a vast global network of computers, sensors, and equipment that is continually at risk of being breached by adversaries.  Despite heavy investments in security and cyber defense, the sheer ubiquity and interconnectedness of DoD equipment leave open the possibility of intrusion through a myriad of means including advanced persistent threats (APTs).  Such threats take many forms, such as Trojans, back-doors in embedded systems, worms, spear-phishing, and viruses, all of which could prove detrimental to the war-fighter if not discovered. Recent examples of such advanced attacks include Stuxnet and Flame.   Detecting such threats requires novel techniques that are not signature based, since such attacks (or, at the very least, the most dangerous ones) are often customized for a particular target, perhaps based upon substantial intelligence gathering.Accordingly, we intend to use the SKAION 2009 DARPA Dataset to test our novel anomaly detection algorithms.  This data set will provide both background "signal" into which we can inject our own anomalous measurements, as well as providing a data set with its own inherent anomalies.  Our main computational tools will be advanced ideas from multi-sensor fusion, compressed sensing, and dependency analysis.This work is currently being funded by the Office of the Secretary of Defense under contract #W911QX-13-C-0015.

reason: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks. Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node. This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies. This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.

reason: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks. Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node. This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies. This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.

reason: During the early days of the Information Age routine network security was often as simple as monitoring log files or writing scripts, but with modern advents such as Cluster and Grid computing global network traffic has increased from 0.001 PB/month (1990) to 27,483 PB/month (2011).  Simply put, the volume of data is now unmanageable by human operators or even intrusion detection scripts.  Our research aims to utilize software Intelligent Agents (IA's) and IBM InfoSphere Streams to develop a framework that performs realtime (sub-second) data analytics on network traffic.  The IA's receive inbound network data and use machine-learning algorithms to dynamically assess and counter cyber attacks.  Our organization will use data provided by PREDICT to provide an initial 'training' sandbox environment for the IA's.  This seed data will allow the IA's to gain knowledge about the network topology, packet structures, methods of attack, and learn what a 'normal' (no attacks occurring) stream of traffic should look like.  After the initial training of the IA's a different data set will be used to test the learning capabilities and response actions of the IA's, allowing our organization to perform a rigorous analysis on the performance of our framework.
datasetOrg: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

reason: In this research project, we'll evaluate various IP reputation, DNSBL and DNSWL (email Spam black- and whitelists based on DNS), and BGP based feeds for their relevancy, using the PREDICT data sets. Scope of this research is Network IPS (Intrustion Prevention Systems) and enhancing them with IP reputation technology. We've selected the two data sets, which both have real non-anonymized IP address records, and are updated on the regular basis. We'll validate these real IP addresses against various reputation feeds and estimate False Positive, False Negative rates as well as overall hit and match rate.

reason: We are requesting the Data for the project PEARL (described below). Please note that the people with access to the data are all US Citizens)PEARL Ã¢Â€Â“ Preempt Evolve Act Review Learn (PEARL) PEARL incorporates a trust management framework and learning system with the ultimate goals of identifying those entities in the environment that are not trustworthy, and responding to potential threats in an automated, real-time fashion. Changes in trust levels over time, we suggest, provide an indication of the behavior of a node. The changes are used by PEARL to make a decision as to how to react. PEARL will be given knowledge of the trust relationships in the environment, will assign trust values to those relationships (per node), and will maintain a history of past trust values. The system will then use changes in trust values over time to identify patterns of behavior and decide how to react.

reason: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks.  Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node.   This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies.  This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.

reason: We are requesting the Data for the project PEARL (described below). Please note that the people with access to the data are all US Citizens)PEARL Ã¢Â€Â“ Preempt Evolve Act Review Learn (PEARL) PEARL incorporates a trust management framework and learning system with the ultimate goals of identifying those entities in the environment that are not trustworthy, and responding to potential threats in an automated, real-time fashion. Changes in trust levels over time, we suggest, provide an indication of the behavior of a node. The changes are used by PEARL to make a decision as to how to react. PEARL will be given knowledge of the trust relationships in the environment, will assign trust values to those relationships (per node), and willmaintain a history of past trust values. The system will then use changes in trust values over time to identify patterns of behavior and decide how to react.
